Makurdi  – Asiwaju Bola Tinubu, the All Progressives Congress (APC) presidential aspirant, on Tuesday said he will not retire from politics until he becomes president of Nigeria. The APC national leader and former governor of Lagos State disclosed this while speaking with delegates of the party in Benue State ahead of the presidential primaries of the party. He, however, noted that there would be no contest whatsoever between him and whoever eventually emerges as the standard flag bearer of the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP). -Advertisement- While he rekindled hope of a better Nigeria, he pledged that if elected president, he would run a transparent and open government to the admiration of Nigerians. The former Lagos State governor stated that when he becomes president, he would bring to bear the experience of his leadership style as Lagos State governor on Nigeria. Asiwaju, who observed that Nigeria is a rich country, noted that what the nation needs was to redirect and channel its resources in the right direction. Earlier, Senator Kashim Shettima, who spoke at the occasion, insisted that Senator Tinubu was the right person to take Nigeria to the promised land. He also extolled the virtues of Senator Joseph Tarka as a leader and emancipator of minority interest groups in Nigeria